Ringleader Putin
Medical experts from Moscow, Germany, France, and Sweden agree: Alexei Navalny is a victim of the nerve agent Novichok. Navalny is President Putin's largest opponent and the founder of the Anti-Corruption Foundation.
Fortunately, Navalny's survival has prevented a deterioration in relations between Russia and Germany.
To demonstrate her "clear stance," Chancellor Merkel declared Navalny to be "a victim of persecution due to freedom of speech."
In her view, this incident is extremely serious, and only the Russian government can and must respond.
She emphasizes that the whole world needs an explanation.
Merkel has called on the Russian authorities to launch an independent and transparent investigation.
The European Union and the United Kingdom also support this call.
If the result of the investigation proves that the Russian government is the perpetrator of the event, the European Commission will impose new sanctions.
However, according to the Convention on the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons, poisoning is prohibited behavior.
This is not the first time the Putin government has used the nerve agent Novichok to deal with its political enemies.
In 2018, former Russian double agent Sergey Skripal and his daughter Yulia were poisoned on British soil.
Both of them survived and hid.
The Kremlin strongly denied both incidents.
Regarding the Navalny case, Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov insisted that "there is no evidence to implicate the Russian government."
Russian Foreign Intelligence Service head Sergei Naryshkin even says this is the behavior of Western intelligence agencies, blaming the Russian government's credit for it.
Naryshkin's statement is obviously an excuse, but he also stated a fact: the Navalny case is detrimental to Russia.
Using a toxic substance on a famous political opponent just before the election, and using a Soviet-developed toxin, is inexcusable.
Especially at a time when Belarusian citizens are protesting the August election, this timing is intriguing.
Moreover, the Kremlin's initial reaction to the Navalny case was particularly puzzling.
Shouldn't the Russian government have planned more carefully before carrying out the crime?
If it's really the Russian government that did it, as Germany claims, then this murder was also a failed operation.
Putin has always been the Darth Vader (the primary antagonist of the movie Star Wars) of the international political arena, interfering in US elections, inciting street protests in France, luring the UK out of the EU, and propping up Bashar al-Assad in Syria.
As a former KGB agent, he is intelligent, far-sighted, and cunning.
Then why can't he kill Skripal and Navalny?
Why can Navalny escape to Germany? And he was even quickly diagnosed with being poisoned?
Now, Putin is facing international condemnation and sanctions, and the Nord Stream 2 natural gas pipeline project to Germany is facing cancellation.
This assassination attempt is obviously not worth it.
In fact, this has only fueled public opposition to the evil deeds of the Russian authorities.
Even if it wasn't Putin who did it, the claim that it was the West's intelligence agencies is even more excessive.
If such accusations are true, scientists from Germany and Sweden wouldn't talk about the facts of the nerve agent Novichok.
More likely it could be a plot orchestrated by Putin's political circle.
Maybe Putin needed Navalny to shut up before the elections, or maybe he caused trouble with his anti-corruption investigation.
In Russia, you can buy various products and services on the black market, including military-grade nerve agents.
Putin's politcal enforcers are loyal but stupid, they thought poisoning Navalny was a good idea, only a few involved know the truth.
Other failed poisoning attempts share similar characteristics: the poisoning of journalist Vladimir Kara-Murza in 2015 and 2017. Kara-Murza is the coordinator of the Public Investigation Committee of Khodorkovsky.
The poisoning of independent news website Mediazona publisher Peter Verzilov in 2018.
Mediazona is a website that reports on the abuse of power by Russian law enforcement.
This can be traced back even further to 2006, the poisoning of former KGB agent Alexander Litvinenko, who frequently criticized Russia's security agencies.
Such poisonings, like the case of Navalny, often have counterproductive effects.
2004, liberal newspaper "Novaya Gazeta" columnist Anna Politkovskaya was poisoned on a plane from Moscow to Beslan, although she survived, but was shot dead two years later in an apartment building elevator.
As Putin said, her death brought huge damage to the image of the Russian government.
This is not an excuse for the Kremlin.
No matter whether Putin personally commanded it, the system he created allowed such crimes to occur. This system is both ineffective and useless, and is a farce involving shameless actors.
Navalny's death is the desired result of the Kremlin, and it's the final goal of the lickspittles to satisfy their master Putin.
Only loyalty matters in Putin's inner circle.
Even if the poisoning fails, they won't be punished.
Because they're doing it for the benefit of the president.
Those looking for proof of the poisoning might be disappointed.
Despite this, the Kremlin is the main culprit.
Western countries must make it clear that even if their own economy is affected, they should impose sanctions on Russia.
Putin has created a system centered around himself.
All the responsibilities that occur in Russia are attributed to himself.
